I’m not fucking Sun Tzu or whatever but sanctions are designed to quash the lower classes and not those in charge. Political consequences for this have to target the leader’s ability to exert influence. The invasion is already unpopular in Russia; sanctions won’t change anything.

We’re gonna sanction and starve a bunch of Russian peasants, act like we did something to stop Putin even though he’s one of the richest men on earth and an autocrat who won’t be affected by any of it, then pat ourselves on the back. Rinse and repeat with Belarus, Georgia, etc.

No shit it didn’t HAVE to result in invasion and attempted annexation of sovereign land, that is obviously Putin’s fault. But the US does this over and over and over to weaker countries and never acknowledges their role in the aftermath.

The result for them has been the biggest drop in life expectancy since WWII & social collapse. Of course a nationalist dictator bent on restoring their former glory was going to be the inevitable consequence of a stymied, declining empire. We learned absolutely nothing from WWI.

My Ukraine take is the West needs to own up to their role in creating the political conditions that led to the invasion of Ukraine. Putin’s rise and fomentation of Russian nationalism happened directly because of the West kneecapping Russia following the collapse of the USSR.

I posted it and will probably post a lot more in the future. I’m still working through it & sometimes typing it out and putting it out there grants me clarity. All love to anyone else struggling with ED & learning to love themselves in a world that’s paid to tell you otherwise ❤️

And I’m beginning to learn what it’s like to truly love my body and myself from within, not based on some external standards of worthiness. I have good days and bad days, but I’m constantly getting better.

Giving up restricting is the best gift you will ever give yourself. ❤️

Now I’m settling into a weight that’s healthy for me and am unlearning restrictive ideas & behaviors like feeling guilty after eating a full meal or punishing myself for overeating with exercise. I’m also eating more of my “fear foods” again like peanut butter, cheese, & nuts. 💕

You do NOT have to be medically underweight or even close for your current weight to be unhealthily low. Some bodies (like mine) simply have higher set points than others. If you find you gain weight after even one “slip-up,” it’s likely due to unhealthy or excessive restriction.

I never even got below 22 BMI, yet  I still experienced health effects like missing periods/severe PMS, low libido, extreme depression, constipation, near-constant brain fog...I only realized after recovery that these symptoms were caused by undereating and chronic restriction.

My body has been BEGGING me to gain weight for so long, but I refused simply because I believed that I’m “supposed” to be much smaller. Total bullshit.

So much of what is held up as common knowledge about nutrition & health is completely misinformed or fabricated altogether.

TW: eating disorder

I’ve had a binge & restrict ED for 1.5+ years and NOBODY, including me, ever realized until about a month ago. So few people grasp the true scope of eating disorders. They are so tragically commonplace that signs of ED are often dismissed as normal behavior.

Everyone should strive to listen to their bodies cues for fuel. This goes beyond waiting for my tummy to rumble. For me, mood, energy, etc. are often better indicators.

As well, be mindful of WHY your cravings are present (are you hungry or just tired, bored, thirsty, etc.?)

Intuitive eating is an overcorrection for elimination dieting. Some foods ARE better for you than others. Sugar, alcohol, etc. are highly addictive and cause a host of devastating health effects. Enjoy these things in moderation, but be mindful of their effects on your body.

As well, rules and structure around eating are not inherently bad. Sure, a recovering orthorexic would benefit from a more lax approach to food, but allowing yourself to “honor” or give in to every single craving can result in addictive food behavior and poor health.

Inversely, certain foods spike your insulin and alter your satiety cues. It’s why you can eat a slice of cake and feel hungrier than before. There is no way to eat “intuitively” if you allow yourself to consumes foods that disrupt your hormonal balance.

Ghrelin (your hunger hormone) is released in ANTICIPATION of food, regardless of how hungry you actually are. If you start skipping breakfast or eating at a later time than usual, your hunger signals will adapt.

The first is that intuitive eating presumes you have no ability to positively shape your hunger cues.

In reality, your hunger signals are governed largely by your consumption habits and can be augmented, for better or worse, by altering your eating routine.

I’ve believed my whole life that I am just a lazy, unmotivated person when that couldn’t be further from the truth. 

I am not lazy. I work my ass off every goddamn day. I may not have as much to show for it as others, but I’m proud to have gotten this far & of my accomplishments

On the outside, normal people look at us ADHD folks and think we’re lazy. Even I’m guilty of it. In reality, we are constantly working 10x harder than everyone else just to meet baseline expectations.

The worst part is that nobody has any sympathy for what me and my fellow ADHD-brains go through. In fact, they often openly mock us for it.

When I tell people I am struggling with my ADHD, I can feel them resist the urge to snicker and write it off as histrionic excuse-making.

The reward centers in my brain do not function properly. You know, the thing that...makes you do literally anything. 
That part, that existentially VITAL part of my brain, doesn’t work. 

The only way I can complete any task is if it HAS to be done RIGHT NOW or ELSE.

You can’t enjoy even the most basic activities. You can’t sit down and watch a movie. You can’t finish reading a book. You can’t get through a full workout. You have to be constantly bombarded with stimuli just to escape your own mind or you start to feel like you’re going insane

A parent who chooses to send their child to school because they deserve a quality education is making a difficult but valid decision. It’s not frivolous, it’s not political, it’s just parents trying to do what they think is right for their kid in an impossibly difficult position.

It is unfortunate but true that virtual classrooms are NOT meeting the needs of students with special learning needs. Moreover, many families are at work and just can’t keep their kids at home during the day. It is myopic to blame the parents and individuals in these situations.

I’ve made this point elsewhere but here it is again: I do not judge families who have chosen in-person schooling this year, especially SpEd/ESL students.

So many left-leaning people are writing off these families’ concerns when in reality they face an extremely tough choice.
Just want to clarify that reopening schools is not safe and should not be happening, so I am grading on a scale that ranges from disconcerting to pre-apocalyptic.

Things will change as more students enroll in-person (which we expect). For now, it is nice to see the kids IRL again and to give students who could not learn virtually (due to access or ability) the chance to do so.
